explanation.content:
# JavaScript Objects

An **object** groups related data and behaviour into one named container. Think of a student's record card: it has a name field, an age field, and a GPA field — all belonging to the same person. An object in JavaScript is exactly this: a set of **key-value pairs**.

```javascript
const student = {
    name:      "Priya Sharma",
    age:       21,
    gpa:       3.8,
    isActive:  true,
};
```

## Accessing Properties

```javascript
student.name         // "Priya Sharma" — dot notation
student["name"]      // "Priya Sharma" — bracket notation

const key = "age";
student[key]         // 21 — dynamic key using bracket notation
```

## Adding, Updating, and Deleting

```javascript
student.email   = "priya@example.com";  // add
student.gpa     = 3.9;                  // update
delete student.isActive;                // remove
```

## Methods — functions as properties

An object's value can be a function. Such a property is called a **method**:

```javascript
const account = {
    balance: 5000,
    deposit(amount) {
        this.balance += amount;
    },
    getBalance() {
        return this.balance;
    },
};

account.deposit(1000);
console.log(account.getBalance()); // 6000
```

`this` inside a method refers to the object the method belongs to.

## Object Destructuring

```javascript
const { name, age, city = "Unknown" } = student;
// Extracts name, age, and city (defaulting to "Unknown")
```

## Iterating Over an Object

```javascript
for (const key in student) {
    console.log(`${key}: ${student[key]}`);
}

Object.keys(student)     // array of keys
Object.values(student)   // array of values
Object.entries(student)  // array of [key, value] pairs
```

In the code example below, you will see an object with methods, destructuring, and `Object.entries()` used in a bank account simulation.

codeExample.code:
// Bank Account Object — properties and methods

const account = {
    owner:        "Rahul Sharma",
    balance:      10000,
    transactions: [],

    deposit(amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) return "Invalid amount.";
        this.balance += amount;
        this.transactions.push({ type: "deposit", amount });
        return `Deposited ₹${amount}. New balance: ₹${this.balance}`;
    },

    withdraw(amount) {
        if (amount <= 0)          return "Invalid amount.";
        if (amount > this.balance) return "Insufficient funds.";
        this.balance -= amount;
        this.transactions.push({ type: "withdraw", amount });
        return `Withdrew ₹${amount}. New balance: ₹${this.balance}`;
    },

    statement() {
        console.log(`\n--- Statement: ${this.owner} ---`);
        this.transactions.forEach((t, i) => {
            console.log(`  ${i + 1}. ${t.type}: ₹${t.amount}`);
        });
        console.log(`  Balance: ₹${this.balance}`);
    },
};

console.log(account.deposit(5000));
console.log(account.withdraw(2000));
console.log(account.withdraw(20000));  // fails
account.statement();

// Destructure properties
const { owner, balance } = account;
console.log(`\n${owner}'s balance: ₹${balance}`);

